post_text:
We should be celebrating commencements today, but it seems the universe had other plans. There is so much about this strange and interesting time that we’ll always remember. Large scale cultural and societal events have a way of impacting people and their habits for decades. May this make us all stronger, wiser, and more resilient. Garber Dukes don’t shrink; we persevere and stare down adversity…it is who we are.
I sincerely hope that we continue to look for silver-linings and strive to find and make the best of every situation that comes our way, especially the tough ones. For many reasons, I know the class of 2020 will be among the most memorable in the history of Garber High School.
We’re proudly displaying the names of our graduates on yard signs at Garber. These signs are a small gift to the Class of 2020. We invite our grads to stop by and pick up their sign to display proudly at their own home. Go Dukes!

Verellen Elementary School
May 27 at 1:28 PM ·

Tuesday, June 2, from 4:00-6:00 p.m. the Verellen staff will be passing out final report cards and yearbooks to those students who previously ordered one. We also have several books we will pass out to keep our students reading this summer. To help with the flow of traffic, please come at the following times if you are able. Last names starting with A-M from 4:00-5:00 p.m., last names starting with N-Z from 5:00-6:00 p.m. This will be a drive through distribution with your teachers and staff members present to wave good bye and to wish you a fun and safe summer.

If you are not available for this event, you can pick up your report card on Wednesday, June 3 between 8:00 – 11:45 a.m. Otherwise, they will be mailed at a later date.

Congratulations to Cramer teacher Mary Knochel for being named the Outstanding CSO Adviser for 2019-20 by SVSU. Chief Science Officers serve as a voice for STEM, identifying opportunities such as speakers, field trips, and science nights, as well as ensuring such opportunities reflect the interests and desires of their peers. They help increase exposure of existing STEM programs such as robotics, code clubs, and science fairs.

Thank you to Mrs. Knochel for her time, effort, and committment to the CSO program.

post_text: Congratulations Keegan!
shared_text:
Essexville Garber High School
May 21 at 7:00 PM ·

#seniorspotlight #GarberDukes #Classof2020 #WearetheDukes

𝗞𝗲𝗲𝗴𝗮𝗻 𝗖𝗵𝗿𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗼𝗽𝗵𝗲𝗿 𝗞𝗶𝗻𝘀𝗲𝗹𝗹𝗮 🎓

Keegan started at Essexville-Hampton Public Schools in the 6th grade at Cramer Junior High School, after attending St. John's Pre-K through 5th grade!

Throughout his academic career, Keegan played Football 🏈 (4 years), Track 👟 (3 years) and Basketball 🏀 (2 years). Garber Athletic Association - GAA

Mrs. Dawn Bromberg has greatly influenced Keegan. She taught him knowledge that he felt he could put to use and her style of teaching kept him engaged.

Keegan's advice to underclassmen would be to not take any high school privilege for granted because you never know when those privileges can be taken away.

One of Keegan's many favorite memories at Garber was making it to the State Track and Field finals in 2019. He competed in the 4 x 200 and 4 x 400 meter relays. 🎉

After graduation, Keegan will attend Delta College and then transfer to a 4 year university to pursue a career in Sales/Marketing.

𝗖𝗼𝗻𝗴𝗿𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗹𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝗞𝗲𝗲𝗴𝗮𝗻!

Joseph also attended the Bay-Arenac ISD Career Center for two years where he studied and trained in both Auto Mechanics and Welding. Two of Joe's favorite memories were the all night Computer Lan Parties on some weekends and the other was the time Joe helped deliver pizza to solider friends of the family returning to Afghanistan aboard a "Chinook " helicopter.

Dakota has over come many many obstacles in his life and has learned to be a fighter at a young age.

Throughout his academic career, Dakota has played some sports (Basketball & Wrestling) but it just wasn't for him! His true 'loves' in life are Hunting 🦌, Fishing 🎣, Air Soft and Paintball.

This young man is a very kind and caring person, and he will always be there to help-you can ALWAYS count on Dakota! Friends mean a lot to him, and he cherishes every one he has.

Dakota has volunteered for Camp Quality Michigan as a Camp Companion. This camp is held for Kids with Cancer, and he has attended as a camper for several years. Dakota knew that he could give back to kids going though the same thing he did. 🎗💜

After graduation, Dakota will attend Delta College to begin with his basics and decide which career pathway he would like to pursue afterwards: Small Engine Repair or Law Enforcement.

~From Dakota's Family~ We love you and we are always behind you in all your choices!

post_text: Great idea!
shared_text:
Bush Elementary
May 4 at 10:18 PM ·

In January, we had begun to honor each child in our school family by honoring children as School Family Members of the Week.

Upon school being cancelled, there were still 94 children to be honored as such. We wanted to find a way to be sure that each child in our school family is recognized before the year is done.

We did the math and found that we can still honor the 94 remaining children by honoring 4-5 students per day as our School Family Members of the Day. Their photos and All About Me Banners will be posted here daily and in our Bush School Parent group. Mrs. Schingeck will also announce and celebrate School Family Members of the Day on her 11:00 Live Character Education/Music Lesson right here on Facebook Live.

Every student is an important member of Bush School Family, and we celebrate you!

Throughout his 4 years at Garber High, he has played both baseball ⚾️ AND basketball 🏀 for six years (7th - 12th grade). @Garber wth

Jameson has been greatly influenced by Mr. Brian Kloha, who inspired him to pursue classes in the industrial arts and technical drawing. This has led Jameson to discover his future career pathway!

Jameson's favorite memory was the basketball district semi-final game against Swan Valley in March of 2020. He scored 24 points and had 11 rebounds! "The support from students, staff, administrators, former coaches, and parents was amazing and the atmosphere in the gym was electric!"

After graduation, Jameson will pursue a Bachelor's in Mechanical Engineering at Michigan State University! GO GREEN!

This beautiful lady has a passion for. . .DANCE! Lauren has participated on the Garber Dance Team for 4 years (Garber Athletic Association - GAA) while dancing competitively at Miss Lore's School of Performing Arts on Dance Rage for 14 years.

Through the many hours of dance practice outside of school, her active involvement has not hindered her academics at Garber. She was invited her Junior year to the National Honor Society for her outstanding GPA and has served as a member for 2 years.

Lauren loves spending time with her sister, and would like to share the following message to our underclassmen "never take a day for granted and live life to the fullest. Don't be afraid to push yourself out of your comfort zone"

Stephanie has shared many memories at Garber High but one of her favorites to date would be having fun during the Spring Break 2018 Training with her fellow teammates and GHS Baseball players singing Karaoke 🎤 ( check out the comments on this post for the video clip- we think you're a triple threat Steph!)

post_text:
Parents,
Did you know your free/reduced lunch application coverage is now expanded to include extra EBT benefits for your student? If your student is on a free/reduced application you will now receive extra food cash each month during the COVID-19 pandemic.

If you are interested in this benefit, you can submit a new application at www.lunchapp.com. The process is easy and you will need your student's ID number. After you are approved, the EBT card will arrive in the mail in early May.

If you have any questions, please contact Melissa Pavlik at (989) 460-2386
text:
Parents,
Did you know your free/reduced lunch application coverage is now expanded to include extra EBT benefits for your student? If your student is on a free/reduced application you will now receive extra food cash each month during the COVID-19 pandemic.

If you are interested in this benefit, you can submit a new application at www.lunchapp.com. The process is easy and you will need your student's ID number. After you are approved, the EBT card will arrive in the mail in early May.

If you have any questions, please contact Melissa Pavlik at (989) 460-2386

Hello,
We will be holding our food distribution tomorrow (Tuesday, March 31st) and Thursday, April 2nd from 10 a.m. to Noon at Garber High School. This program is free for any child 18 years and under. Children do not need to be present for pick up and a delivery option is available. Over the last two weeks, we have given out almost 21,000 meals. Please contact Melissa Pavlik, Food Service Director, at (989)460-2386 for more information.

post_text: Join us for Garber High Schools' annual Spring Musical in March 2020. Garber High School continues its long-standing tradition of excellence in musical theatre with this fun, high-energy, quirky musical. The cast includes over 50 talented Garber students singing and dancing their way with Elle Woods (Skyler Walton) to Harvard Law to follow boyfriend Warner Huntingon III (Andrew Neumann). Along the way, she meets exciting friends like silly hair stylist Paulette Buonofuonte (Madison Woodfin), down to earth law student Emmett Forrest (Noah Bach), and brunette enemies like Vivienne Kensington (Meri McGinnis). Elle goes in search of Warner, but finds the meaning of true friendship, the power of hard work and perseverance, and a love for a career she never dreamed of. Join Elle and the cast of Legally Blonde for a night you won't forget!

What a heart-warming moment at our JV boys basketball game against Bridgeport this week. One of our JV players, Alex Couture, who is the team manager, had the opportunity to play in the game. Alex is a very spirited student who participates in multiple sports. His eagerness to be involved is an inspiration to everyone who knows him. Bridgeport showed outstanding sportsmanship both during and after the game. Thank you to our JV coach Vic Talaga, players on both teams, Garber coaching staff, and the Bridgeport players and coaches for creating such a memorable moment for Alex!

Legendary basketball coach John Wooden said it best “What you are as a person is far more important than what you are as a basketball player.”

post_text:
Congratulations to the Boys’ Varsity Swim Team on a fantastic showing at the ISC Championships this weekend. Podium finishers were Josh Bilodeau, Andrew Woods, Caleb
Bebb, Caleb Smale, Chance Owen, Seth Gage, Ethan Sutter, Cameron Callahan, and Matthew Killey.

ISC Champions were Josh Bilodeau in the 200 freestyle, Andrew Woods in the 200 IM and the 100 breaststroke both at State Qualifying times, and the 400 Freestyle Relay consisting of Josh Bilodeau, Matthew Killey, Caleb Smale and Andrew Woods.

Andrew was also named Swimmer of the Meet. Congratulations team on a wonderful season and good luck to Andrew at States!

shared_text:
Essexville-Hampton Bands
February 29 at 7:46 PM ·

Congratulations to the Garber Symphonic and Concert bands on their fine performances at District band festival this past Saturday. The Symphonic band received 3 first division ratings and 1 second division with an overall first division rating and the Concert band received 4 first division ratings for an overall first division rating. This marks the 18th straight year that the Symphonic band has received a first division rating and the 17th straight year that the Concert band has. Way to go band students! We also wanted to give a huge thanks to all the parent who chaperoned for us.

shared_text:
Garber Athletic Association - GAA
February 24 at 5:44 PM ·

Congratulations to the Boys & Girls Bowling Teams!

Both the boys’ and girls’ bowling teams won the TVC conference team championship on Friday.
In Singles on Saturday, Ireland Michalak placed 2nd, Maya Janowicz 5th and Alena Grawburg 7th. Ireland, Maya and Alena were also selected to the 1st team all conference while Taylor Osterhout made the 2nd team. In boys singles Braedyn Hofmeister was 1st and Zach Moore was 9th. Braedyn was selected to the 1st team all conference while Zach made the 2nd team. Jonah Przepiora and Nicholas Brody were honorable mention.

Go Dukes!! 🎳

We wanted to remind everyone that we have a half-day tomorrow due to Professional Development.

Bush students will be dismissed at 11:35 a.m. Students will be having lunch at school before the end of the school day. A sack lunch is available through our hot lunch program.

Verellen students will be dismissed at 11:21. The Boys and Girls club will be open from dismissal until 6:00 p.m.

Cramer students will be released at 12:00 p.m. Buses will run their normal routes, however, a regular lunch will not be served. There will be a Grab & Go sack lunch available for purchase when students are released at 12:00. Also, Cramer will have 6th-8th grade Parent/Teacher Conferences on Thursday from 4:00 to 6:00.

Garber students will be released at 11:45. Buses will depart at 12:15, and they will run their normal routes. Grab and Go sack lunches will be available for purchase after school. Garber’s Parent-Teacher Conferences will be held on December 10th from 4:00 - 6:30.

post_text: Thank you to the Smigiel family for their generous gift. We are fortunate to have such wonderful, dedicated staff and community members!
shared_text:
Paul Sansburn is with Spencer Smigiel and 4 others.
November 15, 2019 at 7:59 PM ·

As we finish up our last day of school before our 5th Grade Trip to Hartley Outdoor EducationCenter, I want to take a minute to share a heart-warming event that took place yesterday. On Thursday Donna Smigiel came to school to present the 2nd Annual Ryan Smigiel Scholarship to one extremely deserving young lady, Lily Dorion.

Last year I met with the Smigiel Family as they wanted to establish a way to carry on Ryan’s legacy. Ryan was a former 5th grade student and high school counselor of mine that attended the Center.

As a group we established criteria that really defined the incredible characteristics and qualities that Ryan shared with all throughout his life. I shared stories about Ryan and his incredible journey and fight, it was truly an inspiration to all. A questionnaire for students was developed, we got input from teachers and administration, and made our selection. Lily will proudly represent Ryan’s legacy and is extremely thankful! Thank you to the entire Smigiel Family💚💚💚

shared_text:
Garber Athletic Association - GAA
November 11, 2019 at 6:42 PM ·

Congratulations on a strong finish to the season! Girls Varsity Swim are the 2019 ISC Championship Runners Up! Multiple podium finishers and medalists include Hailey Dowd 2nd in the 200 IM, Jenna Miller 2nd in diving, Grace Miller 3rd in the 500 free and the 2nd place 200 freestyle relay consisting of Lauren Herek, Jenna Miller, Kortney Kotenko and Hailey Dowd. Other podium finishers include Jordan Kruskie, Sydney Shannon, Cate Woods, Mya Sutter, Haley Parisson, Clair Ulman and Lizzie Osborn. Congrats to all the swimmers and a great season and a fantastic finish!

Go Dukes!

post_text: Great job by Cramer staff to bring awareness to Red Ribbon Week and Bullying Prevention Month this week!
shared_text:
Cramer Junior High School
October 25, 2019 at 7:57 PM ·

In celebration of Red Ribbon Week and October being Anti Bullying Month, Cramer Junior High will be Dressing Up next week. The attached flier will highlight each day's theme.

Red Ribbon Week and Anti Bullying Campaigns are an ideal way for people and communities to unite and take a visible stand against drugs, alcohol and bullying while promoting kindness and healthy choices.

Cramer will be decked out with Red Ribbons (Drug and Alcohol awareness) and Blue Ribbons (Anti Bullying). In addition to dressing up to show support, students will have the opportunity to participate in theme related activities and games at lunch, win prizes and learn about staying healthy and standing up to support each other in kindness.

post_text: Thank you to the Garber football program for their efforts to raise money for the Bouckaert family. Their son Brandon has been battling brain cancer. Garber football sold bracelets with the phrase "Tackling Cancer". At Monday's school board meeting, JV Coach Sansburn and Varsity Coach Coquillard presented the Bouckaert family with a check for $1,500 to help with medical expenses.

shared_text:
Essexville-Hampton Bands
October 9, 2019 at 1:11 AM ·

The bands annual March-a-Thon is this Sunday October, 13th at 6:30 at the Gqrber Football Field. The Marching Dukes will be performing their halftime show and then we will begin the March-a-thon. This is the band's biggest fundraiser and it is what allows us to run the program that we have here at EHPS. The proceeds from the fundraiser go towards new instruments, music, uniforms, scholarships and also to help offset the cost of supplies for our students among many other things. Please consider donating to a student who is collecting pledges for the group.

Additionally: band parents, we could still use help collecting money and serving food on Sunday. Just contact Mr. Lewis at lewisj@e-hps.net or 460-2421 if you can help.

We want to remind everyone that there is no school tomorrow due to a teacher professional development day.

Boys/Girls located at Verellen is closed tomorrow, Wednesday, October 9th

Bush Daycare will be open tomorrow, Wednesday, October 9th

Homecoming is this week. The powderpuff game is scheduled for 7:00 p.m. on Thursday. The Homecoming parade is Friday starting at 4:15 p.m. A map of the parade route is posted on our facebook page. The Hall of Fame dinner will be at 5:00 p.m. The football game starts at 7:00 p.m. and the homecoming court will be announced during halftime.

The Garber Family Reunion is tomorrow from 5 - 7:30 p.m. There will be $5 wristbands for bounce houses and train rides. We will also have a $5 combo meal (available at the concession stand.)

The Duke Dash Race & Family Fun Day is this Saturday from 11:00 a.m.-2:00 p.m. Registration begins at 11:00 a.m. with the 5k starting at noon and the kids' fun run at 1:30 p.m. We have medals for all participants with special recognition to our top runners in each age bracket. Games, pumpkin decorating, face painting, hot cocoa, and bounce houses from 11:00 a.m.-2:00 p.m. Register by Friday for the best price! Don't forget to wear your blue and white Duke gear!!!

post_text: Essexville-Hampton Public Schools is aware of a rumor of a threat made by a person in Bay City. We have been communicating closely with our school resource officer and local authorities to assess the situation. Our School resource officer has been in all of our buildings today as we continue to assess the situation. It was not necessary to adjust our normal safety procedures. As a precaution, local authorities to include Essexville and Hampton Township Public Safety Departments have dedicated additional patrol around our schools today. Our first priority is always the safety of our students and staff.

Join us tomorrow night at 6:00 p.m. (doors open at 5:30) for the StraightTalk presentation. The program provides insight and intervention tools for parents and loved ones of someone in an active addiction while breaking the stigma of addiction. The program also supports the battle against the opiod crisis.

We want to thank the following organizations for their generous support:
Frankenmuth Credit Union
Saginaw Valley Adjusters Association
Frankenmuth Insurance Company

We also want to extend a special thank you to Chuck and Ruth McMartin and family for all of their efforts to bring this enlightening presentation to Garber High School.
